{
  "description": "CRITICAL: Write tests before production code. Write failing test first (Red), write minimal code to pass (Green), refactor with confidence (Refactor). This is the Red-Green-Refactor cycle.",
  "examples": [
    {
      "do": {
        "description": "Follow Test-Driven Development cycle",
        "content": [
          "Write failing test first (Red)",
          "Write minimal code to pass (Green)",
          "Refactor with confidence (Refactor)",
          "Repeat cycle for each new behavior",
          "",
          "Correct Examples (TDD cycle):",
          "1. RED - Write failing test:",
          "test('calculates order total', () => {",
          "  const order = createOrder({ items: [{ price: 10 }] });",
          "  expect(calculateTotal(order)).toBe(10);",
          "});",
          "// Test fails: calculateTotal doesn't exist",
          "",
          "2. GREEN - Write minimal code:",
          "function calculateTotal(order) {",
          "  return 10; // hardcoded to pass",
          "}",
          "// Test passes",
          "",
          "3. REFACTOR - Improve implementation:",
          "function calculateTotal(order) {",
          "  return order.items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);",
          "}",
          "// Test still passes, code improved",
          "",
          "TDD Benefits:",
          "- Tests prove code works",
          "- Forces good design (testable code)",
          "- Prevents over-engineering",
          "- Provides regression safety",
          "- Documentation of expected behavior"
        ]
      },
      "dont": {
        "description": "Don't write tests after code is done or skip refactoring",
        "content": [
          "Don't write tests after code is done",
          "Don't skip refactoring step",
          "Don't make code too hard to test",
          "",
          "Wrong Examples (not TDD):",
          "1. Write all production code first",
          "2. Add tests afterwards to hit coverage targets",
          "3. Tests hard to write because code not designed for testing",
          "4. Skip refactoring because tests already pass",
          "",
          "Non-TDD Indicators (CHANGE APPROACH):",
          "- Tests written after implementation",
          "- Code hard to test (too many dependencies)",
          "- Tests as afterthought for coverage",
          "- Skipping refactoring step",
          "- Tests don't drive design",
          "",
          "Adopting TDD:",
          "- Start with test, even if simple",
          "- Write minimal code to pass",
          "- Refactor while tests are green",
          "- Repeat for each new behavior",
          "- Let tests drive design decisions",
          "- If code hard to test, that's a design smell"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}



















































